                <head>424. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>The general elections held in India February 15–21, 1967, returned the Congress
                    Party to power with a somewhat reduced majority. A number of prominent political
                    figures were not reelected, most notably Minister of Food and Agriculture
                        <persName corresp="#p_SC1">Chidambara Subramaniam</persName>. <persName
                        corresp="#p_GI1">Indira Gandhi</persName> formed a new government on March
                    13. The most significant addition to her cabinet was Deputy Prime Minister and
                    Minister of Finance Morarji Desai. M.C. <persName corresp="#p_CMAC1"
                        >Chagla</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_SS1">Swaran Singh</persName>, and
                        <persName corresp="#p_CYBYB1">Y.B. Chavan</persName> continued as Ministers
                    of External Affairs, Defense, and Home Affairs, respectively. <persName
                        corresp="#p_RJ1">Jagjivan Ram</persName> replaced <persName corresp="#p_SC1"
                        >Subramaniam</persName> as Minister of Food and Agriculture.</p>
            </div>
